\description{
Standardises outcome model predictions under each named intervention and
reports pairwise causal contrasts (differences, ratios, or odds ratios)
with uncertainty estimates.

For all three causal estimators, \code{contrast()} computes E[Y^a] by setting
each individual's treatment to the intervened value and averaging the fitted
outcome model predictions over the target population. The target population
is controlled by \code{estimand} (or \code{subset} for subgroup effects). The
estimators differ only in how the outcome model was fitted; variance is
computed by the
\strong{unified influence-function engine} \code{variance_if()} (\code{R/variance_if.R}),
which handles all four cases (g-comp, IPW, matching, ICE) via one entry
point. See \code{vignettes/variance-theory.qmd} for the derivation and the
\code{R/variance_if.R} roxygen header for the architecture.
\itemize{
\item \code{"gcomp"}: standard \code{glm}/\code{gam} on the full data; one-model IF
correction via \code{prepare_model_if()} + \code{apply_model_correction()}.
\item \code{"ipw"}: \code{glm_weightit()} fit weighted for the target estimand (ATE/ATT);
IF Channel 2 delegated to \code{prepare_propensity_if()} (WeightIt shortcut via
\code{sandwich::estfun(asympt = TRUE)}), which already accounts for weight
estimation uncertainty.
\item \code{"matching"}: \code{glm()} on the matched sample with match weights; IF is
computed on the matched sample and aggregated cluster-robustly on
\code{matched$subclass} via \code{vcov_from_if(cluster = ...)}.
}
}
\details{
\subsection{Estimands and standardisation}{

For each intervention \code{a}, \code{contrast()} evaluates the intervention function
on the target rows to obtain the intervened treatment vector \code{a(Lᵢ)}, then
computes:

\if{html}{\out{<div class="sourceCode">}}\preformatted{E\[Y^a\] = (1/|S|) Σᵢ∈S Ê\[Y | A = a(Lᵢ), Lᵢ\]
}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}

where \code{S} is the set of rows determined by the estimand:
\itemize{
\item \code{"ATE"}: all rows (full population)
\item \code{"ATT"}: rows where \code{A == 1} (observed treated)
\item \code{"ATC"}: rows where \code{A == 0} (observed controls)
\item \code{subset}: rows satisfying the quoted expression
}

For \code{"gcomp"}, one fit supports multiple estimands because the outcome
model is the same — only the rows averaged over change. For \code{"ipw"} and
\code{"matching"}, the estimand is baked into the weights/matching and cannot
be changed after fitting.
}

